Anonymous Wed 29 Aug 2018 13:31:28 No.17966545 Report
Quoted By: >>17966580 >>17966584 >>17966646 >>17966736
>>17965466
>nowhere close to how actual humans interact regularly
Ehhhh, I see what you mean, but even this comment itself falls under the taste issue. Most dialogue in almost any medium hardly emulates life to a degree. An appeal to reality isn't always the best course of action when you're working with fiction. Someone could interpret bad dialogue as "my hips are moving on their own!" but give "fuck me harder!" a pass, while another person could call "fuck me harder!" cringey while preferring, say, "Yes! Yessss! Theeere!" Bad dialogue is an issue, but we shouldn't trick ourselves into thinking that there is one, easily-ordered "good dialogue" umbrella. There's a plethora of preferences towards naughty dialogue. Some like it rough, some like it natural, some like it wild.

Again, I'm not saying all dialogue comes down to taste, but I feel like we can get a bit tribalistic when it comes down to our favourite writers. "I don't like writer-x therefore his work is shit" sorta tier.
